commentText: I lived in Andalusia for about 5 yrs, in an old pueblo stone townhouse. There were a good handful Brits in our little corner, but most of the neighborhood were ancestral families. We all got along because we spoke to each other, tried or did speak Spanish, and were willing to learn the ways of the locals and enjoy them. We loved it and rarely had issues unless a local house was rented by yobs. Then we all complained.  There's a pecking order we learned in these villages, and is also followed in C. America where I now live in a tiny pueblo. The first time you go in a shop, you're noticed. You may not be served in order of arrival, as customers are given preferential treatment. The second time in the shop, you're fully acknowledged. The third time, you're a customer, and given you're place in the queue. One time my husband was in the local ferreteria, and was given his place in line. Another local customer complained, and the staff explained that my husband was a regular customer. No more complaining.  My Spanish is OK, but as I age, I find I forget more easily. I've always ask for the Spanish word for a new item or action and then write it down in the small notebook I carry. (For me, writing helps cement the memory). I find this often smooths things, as they realize I'm trying to progress my language skills. I always use a second strategy when encountering an English speaking local. I ask for intercambio and correction, and continue in Spanish, trying to learn.   Let's be honest. Most people aren't cut out for expat life. Being away from the constraints of community makes people more of who they are, and hence the inability or lack of effort for some to learn and integrate. The number of times I've heard English speaking people state 'Country X would be perfect if it weren't for the *insert derogatory name for citizens of that country* is too many to count. If you want it like home, stay home. Stop irritating everyone with your complaining.

commentText: Hey, thank you for your video, I feel like you have hit the nail on the head on some points. As a Spaniard, I think that tourism is okay and expats are fine but everything needs to have a balance:   - Expats need to be integrated. It makes no sense to have lage communitites of British (or Germans for that matter) that have lived here for 30 years and still speak no Spanish.  It makes no sense that there are as of now whole towns in Spain with only English or German speaking expats that DEMAND to be spoken in their own language. Expat numbers also need to be managed. As you mentioned in your video, foreigners coming in large numbers & stablishing themselved here when they have better salaries and pensions at home pushes prices up on houses and goods for everyone and totally displaces the local population.  Also, please note that we dont want to sell small old little towns in Castilla to foreigners so they can have have an idillyc holiday spot (which is something that is currently happening), we want our government to diversify the industry and enhance roads and train connections in other territories other than Catalonia and Madrid so we can live in those great places ourselves.   - Tourism needs to be managed. Spain is the second most visited country in the world only behind France. We are set to surpass them and hit 100 million foreign tourists a year before 2030. Now, thats a crazy number.  However, workers are a limited resource in any economy and population in Spain is barely 50M people. If you have such a large tourism sector which is a human intensive industry with low salaries then you have less ingeneers and a smaller industry sector. If you have such a big part of the population working on tourism then you have less productivity. On top of that, tourism need to be diversified: less summer & beaches & cheap booze all-included tourist packages and more around-the-year, high-end, cultural, rural & sustainable tourism. Less tourists spending more тВм.    Ultimately, Spain is not just a playground for northern europeans looking for sunny, cheap holidays. Neither is living here  a god-given right for digital nomads or retired expats looking for cheaper houses, a great public healthcare system and good weather. I feel like some people have become too entitled tbh.  Once again, thank you for making this video and attempting to explain a deeper side to this story and how we Spaniards feel  ЁЯдЧ

I was born and raised in a town in the south of Tenerife (Canary Islands) very close to tourist areas. I remember that as a child, English people came to my parents' store, they had had a house in the next town for 20 years, where they lived for more than 6 months a year, and they only knew how to say hello in Spanish. All their neighbors were English, they spent their time in English pubs, and in the supermarket they had to serve them in their language because they had to please them. With the growth of tourism, foreigners from those same countries begin to arrive but to work, and two or three years ago they fined a pub in Gran Canaria, because the workers did not know a single word in Spanish, and they were told that if they had a business in Spain, they had to know a minimum of Spanish.
 On the other hand, of course we know the importance of tourism, and most of us know that the problem is the control of that tourism. The Canary Islands are one of the key points of tourism in Spain, and have some of the highest poverty rates, with increasingly more expensive homes, not only due to tourist rentals but also luxury or semi-luxury homes intended for foreigners.

commentText: You might want to consider how much control residents have lost everywhere. In the abandoned Spanish town, moving towards preservationist tourism was probably unanimous. In Alicante or Barcelona, private capital still has outsized influence over planning policy, even if the overwhelming majority objects. Democracy everywhere is badly broken. There is no community-driven policy. The people might win a few battles, but in cities they're definitely not in control of their neighborhoods. Everything you mentioned interacts with that problem, including the direction of the local economy: profiteers may want more tourism, people may instead prefer more local self-sufficiency. But the communities have lost control: that's what generates the resentment.

commentText: Very well done. I'm British, and live in Spain, Mallorca, and have been here for almost 22 years. The protests are driven by real problems of affordability, particularly here where accommodation prices are sky high, and wages stubbornly low. The UK  press is so eager to grab onto the 'they don't want you' angle that they happily spin it that way, and the protestors often direct their anger at the wrong people to grab headlines also, so its easy to get a badly skewed version of the issues. I think its fair that nobody wants zero tourism, and equally true that nobody wants uncontrolled tourism, but where the line is drawn is the focus of the debate. Second home ownership is a big problem here for many. Its making some of our local towns unaffordable for normal Spaniards, while digital nomads and wealthy second home owners move in.... but on the other hand, the municipality where I live has a smallish tourism income, but massive, very expensive (20mil+) holiday homes. These are not taking away properties from locals, but are employing half the population (it seems) as builders, gardeners, property managers, cleaners, pool maintenance etc......as you say, its complicated, problems need to be addressed, but nobody is quite sure how.

commentText: I lived in Granada for 2 for years on a working holiday long before covid. It was both affordable and a great place to live! I got fresh fruit & cheeses everyday for next to nothing. Bread & olives were on the daily. The cafes & Arabic tea spots were amazing. The night life was fun & always a great time with tintos & tapas to fuel the evenings. It was a great place to improve my Spanish. In fact, by the time I was leaving Spain, on my way to take my flight back to the US, a lady at the bus station in Madrid recognized my Granada accent & thought I was a native. Also, I was able to take holidays in France & Portugal when I was off work. The trains were so easy & comfortable to get around! The beaches were only an hour away by bus, so a day trip to the beach to hangout with friends was very common. In fact, a boat trip to Morocco from the tip of Spain is only an hour! I was working & getting paid a lot less in Spain, but I lived so much better than in the US! IтАЩm definitely thinking of going back, maybe to Sevilla or Malaga next time, but I wouldnтАЩt mind going back to Granada at all, especially since it will always have a special place in my heart & has become like a second home for me.

Solar time vs clock time: We don't have a later schedule. Not as much as the clock indicates, actually. Our schedules are adapted to the actual time, to solar time. And this is much more noticeable the further west you go. On the Mediterranean coast (Valencia), the time is closer to solar time than on the Atlantic coast (Vigo).  To compare with your city (Valencia), the most similar would be Atlantic City (NJ), Denver (CO), or Reno (NV) (at the same latitude as Valencia).
 We have more than 1 hour difference between the solar and the clock, and must add the Day Save Time in summer, so midday its at 14h (late in Galicia)

commentText: When moving to another country, one can expect to discover a different culture, beliefs, and norms. Unfortunately, too many Americans expect everything to be American and if it is not, then they blame the country, call it antiquated or backwards.While we all have our priorities and  I for example have lived with central AC and central heat, then yes would find it can be unbearable if you choose a place that does not include it. Americans expect drinking tap water or flushable toilets with toilet paper and for many countries/cities, this may not the norm especially in rural areas. (bidets are common).  If these things are important then of course you might become miserable. Moving to another country is very challenging. I am in the process of collecting documents for my Non Lucrative Visa  Spain, and that alone can be challenging. Just adhering to the bureaucracy that Spain is all about will be a challenge for me, but I better get used to it! . All countries are different and especially Latin American countries that do not have the infrastructure throughout the country that perhaps Americans might expect. One has to do research, live it and be able to move if it isn't  a fit. Pros and cons of every country. To each his own. And I seem to overthink everything. I'm gonna risk it and go! (but I also went to school in Valencia to learn Spanish in my younger years) Great video and information. Enjoyed it.

commentText: We Spaniards are pretty fed up with generalizations. First of all, I know civil servants who have gone from receiving dozens of applications to thousands following the huge influx of foreigners and immigrants who have arrived in Spain in a short period of time. If anything, it is you who are causing the bureaucracy to malfunction.    Secondly, bureaucracy is a guarantee, not a headache. Spaniards have no problem with it because we don't start from scratch; you have to do all the paperwork at once, while Spaniards have been doing it since we were little.   Thirdly, most of the bureaucracy in Spain is digitized, but it will depend on whether the administration you are dealing with has the means or not, whether it is large or small. Otherwise, I don't see how these videos help at all if all the information is not contextualized and put into perspective, which is precisely what the social media suffer from, as they are now almost useless for anything other than spreading misinformation or bias.  I think that most foreigners who arrive in a strange country tend to generalize about things they don't yet know, and of course, without any ability to contextualize.  I'm not even going to get into the subject of naps.  Enough with the stereotypes.
